rd|the Kelly Clarkson song|Since U Been Gone|other songs with similar titles|Since You've Been Gone (disambiguation){{!}}Since You've Been Gone}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Since You Been Gone\n| cover      = Since You Been Gone.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]]\n| album      = [[Down to Earth (Rainbow album)|Down to Earth]]\n| A-side     = Since You Been Gone\n| B-side     = Bad Girl\n| released   = {{Release date|1979|08|}}\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref name=\"archive.org\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212180319/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/|title=Vh1 Top 100 Hard Rock Songs|date=12 February 2009|website=}}</ref>\n| length     =3:25\n| label      = [[Polydor]]\n| writer     = [[Russ Ballard]]\n| producer   = [[Roger Glover]]\n| prev_title = LA Connection\n| prev_year  = 1978\n| next_title = [[All Night Long (Rainbow song)|All Night Long]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n\"'''Since You Been Gone'''\" is a song popularized by [[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]] but written by former [[Argent (band)|Argent]] guitarist [[Russ Ballard]] and first released on his 1976 album ''Winning''. \n\n==Cover versions==\nPrior to Rainbow, the Illinois rock band [[Head East]] recorded and released a cover version of the song on their [[Head East (album)|1978 eponymous album]], reaching #46 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. A year later, Rainbow re-recorded the song and released it as a B-side single.  Head East's version of this song was their highest charting single.\n\n[[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]]'s [[cover version]], released in 1979 with [[Graham Bonnet]] on lead vocals, was a [[UK Singles Chart|Top 10]] single in the [[United Kingdom]] and was named the 82nd Best Hard Rock Song of All Time by [[VH1]].<ref name=\"archive.org\"/> Rainbow's version was used in a 2009 [[T-Mobile]] advertisement filmed at [[Liverpool Street station]] in [[London]], England.{{cn|date=May 2014}}\n\nOther cover versions include those by South African [[all-female band]] [[Clout (band)|Clout]] on their 1978 album ''Substitute'' a.k.a ''Clout'', and by former [[The Runaways|Runaways]] vocalist [[Cherie Currie]] as a duet with her sister [[Marie Currie]] on the 1980 album ''[[Messin' with the Boys]]''.  Their version reached #95 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/messin-with-the-boys-mw0000596615/awards |title=Album Search for \"messin with the boys\" |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Alcatrazz]], also fronted by [[Graham Bonnet]], covered the song on the album ''[[Live Sentence]]'' with [[Yngwie Malmsteen]] on guitar, and yet another Bonnet-fronted outfit, [[Impellitteri]], recorded it for their 1988 debut album ''[[Stand in Line]]''.\n\n[[Brian May]] of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] performed the song live on the [[Back to the Light]] tour in 1993, and it appears on the ''[[Live at the Brixton Academy (Brian May album)|Live at the Brixton Academy]]'' multi-format release.\n\n==References== \n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|_v0bDfZytwk|Video of 1976 Russ Ballard performance}}\n*{{YouTube|1P17ct4e5OE|Video of 1979 Rainbow performance}}\n*{{MetroLyrics song|rainbow|since-youve-been-gone}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rainbow (rock band)}}\n\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 songs]]\n[[Category:1979 singles]]\n[[Category:Rainbow (rock band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Russ Ballard]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Roger Glover]]\n[[Category: Rock ballads]]\n\n{{1970s-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "79.136.68.66", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCover versions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Since_You_Been_Gone"}
{"title_page": "List of Yamaha Three-wheeled all-terrain vehicles", "text_new": "<!-- Still creating this page, will come back to it in 48 hours -->\n\n{{Main|Three-wheeler#All-terrain_vehicles}}\n\n[[Yamaha Corporation|Yamaha]] entered the ATC market in 1980, after paying patent-right to Honda to produce their own version of the All Terrain Cycle. Starting Modestly with a 125cc Recreation ATC that would remain the foundation of their line through 1985, the YT125 featured a 2 Stoke engine with sealed airbox with snorkel intake, an autolube oil injection system, and featured a narrow tunnel above the engine that was advertised to make the machine easier to keep stable in precarious situations. Sadly, it also has a reputation for one of the ugliest ATV's ever produced<ref>{{cite web| |url= https://www.outdoorlife.com/articles/hunting/deer-hunting/venison-recipes/2009/08/ugliest-atvs-ever/ |title=10 Ugliest ATV's of all time |website=Outdoor Life.com||accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref> Advertising pointed out the durability of the tires, at a time when Honda ATC's were still known for relatively weak low-pressure ballon tires<ref>{{cite web| |url= http://www.adclassix.com/ads/80yamaha125atv.htm |title=1980 Yamaha YT125G Tri-Moto Advertisement |website=adclassix.com||accessdate=2020-04-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\n\nYamaha followed the YT125 with the introduction of the YT175 in 1982\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n!  scope=\"col\" |{{Infobox Motorcycle\n|name             = Yamaha YT125G Tri-Moto\n|manufacturer     = [[Yamaha]]\n|parent_company   = \n|production       = 1980-1985\n|assembly         =\n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|class            = [[All-terrain vehicle|Recreation ATC]]\n|engine           = {{Convert|123|cc|abbr=on}} [[Radiator (engine cooling)|air-cooled]] [[two-stroke]] [[Single-cylinder engine|single]]\n|bore_stroke      = 56 x 50\n|compression      = 6.4:1\n|top_speed        = <30 Mph \